                             @{b}@{u}E D I T O R I A L@{ub}@{uu}

                             @{u}A Word From Dunkie@{uu}

Welcome to a New Millennium, and another Issue of @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}.  I would like
to take this opportunity to apologise to @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} Readers for the massive
delay in the release of this Issue, but I'm sure you'll all agree that
Christmas & New Year has been a busy time for everyone, and therefore it's
been pretty hard work getting the Articles and Features in for this Issue.
Not to mention, probably like most of you who read @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, I had that
awful Flu Virus in January that was all over the UK, and therefore have not
been in the best of health or frame of mind to compile and write this first
@{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} Issue of the New Millennium :(((

Major changes have taken place in the UK BBS Scene since Last Issue, with
Cumbria and North Yorkshire being wiped off the UK BBS Scene Map as it were,
due to multiple BBS Closures in those Counties.  All in all 10 BBS Closures
were reported to @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, setting another gloomy picture for the UK BBS
Scene.  However, there was a BBS Relaunch in the case of One-2-One BBS in
London, but other than that, there really wasn't any major good news when
talking about the current status of the UK BBS Scene :(((

@{BG fill}@{"Bedlam BBS" Link BedlamBBS}@{BG background} operated by Pete Laird (Co-Editor Of @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}) was seriously
hit by misfortune in early December, when the entire BBS and it's 34,000+
Filebase was lost due to severe Hard-Drive Failure.  This is just one of the
reasons why @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} is so late, as I've been doing everything within my
power to help Pete Laird rebuild @{BG fill}@{"Bedlam BBS" Link BedlamBBS}@{BG background} from scratch and get it back
online, something that we both have finally achieved (though there were
times when we thought we were never going to achieve it), and now after an
absence of a couple of months, the *NEW* @{BG fill}@{"Bedlam BBS" Link BedlamBBS}@{BG background} is back online, serving
the UK BBS Community AGAIN :)))

Other BBS related news, was that The @{BG fill}@{"FluffyNet" Link FluffyNet}@{BG background} Mail Network changed hands
(AGAIN) Mid-December, and now presides in Lincoln rather than in Newport,
Isle Of Wight.  Indeed @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}' own S.N.S (SysOp Of @{BG fill}@{"Skull Monkey BBS" Link SkullMonkeyBBS}@{BG background})
has now the honour of running @{BG fill}@{"FluffyNet" Link FluffyNet}@{BG background}, taking over from it's previous
owner, Steve Clack (SysOp Of @{BG fill}@{"Total Eclipse BBS" Link TotalEclipseBBS}@{BG background}), who sighted problems with
not having the time to operate and maintain @{BG fill}@{"FluffyNet" Link FluffyNet}@{BG background} adequately.

The Millennium Bug...just what was all the fuss about?  Well, although the
Bug didn't really strike as was predicted, some SysOp's Systems were struck,
and a few of this month's closures are down to a Year 2000 Problem, either
with their System or with their BBS Software, so even the AMIGA it appears
did not fully escape the Year 2000 Problem thanks to Software, rather than
Hardware, which is something that SysOps with old 486 PCs probably would
have preferred!!! <GRIN>

The Big Question that's on everyone's lips at the moment, is can the UK BBS
Scene survive in the 21st Century?  Is there room for the BBS amongst the
ever increasing Telecommunications Industry.  I believe there is, and I also
believe that better times are coming, with the introduction of Unmetered
Internet Calls, and ADSL.  Both these could infact benefit the UK BBS Scene,
rather than hinder it.  I think BBSes are going to have adapt to using the
Internet as a means for Users to access them, using TelNet is a good example.
I hope to have more coverage on TelNet in @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} in the not too distant
future, so look out for that, or indeed if you already know about TelNet, or
even use it, then share your knowledge and expertise with the rest of us,
and write to @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} and @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} Readers about it.

The fundamental fact about BBS Survival, is that it is up to YOU, YOU as
SysOps, and YOU as Users.  It has to be a partnership, but the biggest
responsibility lies on SysOps to make the rest of the World know you are
there providing a Service, and making sure that you do indeed provide that
Service.  @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} has been running now for nearly a year, and yet still
it appears that SysOps can't or won't get the message.  They need to really
make an effort in bringing their BBSes into the Public Eye, and as I've said
until I'm blue in the face, ADVERTISING is the key!!!  AMIGA FORMAT, thanks
to my hard work, runs a FREE BBS Adverts Column, regardless whether you are
an AMIGA or PC BBS, it doesn't matter...a BBS is a BBS regardless what
System it runs on.  So, why is it that only a dozen SysOps, out of 191 have
made the effort to use this FREE Service???  Come on guys, you are missing
out on a brilliant opportunity, an opportunity that pays dividends, ask the
SysOps who advertise in AMIGA FORMAT's pages, they'll all tell you the same
story, that they've all had New Users as a result of Advertising, and in my
case, I've been getting an Average of 10 New Users a Month!!!

The UK BBS Scene is dying, we all know that, and there's no point denying
it, but there are those of us out there, who despite all the odds, are
still achieving results, which means that there are people out there, who
still want BBSes, and while ever there's that market, we should do
everything within our power not to disappoint it.  It's far easier for you
to get people to call your BBS, than it is for you to get people BACK to
calling your BBS once you've disappointed them, so let's ALL make an effort
and hold our heads up high and prove the critics wrong...let's take the UK
BBS Scene into the new Millennium...and beyond!!!

See you Next Issue...
