            @{u}A Few Thoughts On The BBS Scene - By Kevin McAspurn@{uu}

Recently I have been reading quite a lot about the BBS Scene, and how much
it has changed due to the rise in popularity of the Internet.  There seems
to be much confusion about how the Scene can survive, given that the BBS
could appear irrelevant alongside the cheap access, and fancy Graphics of
the Web.  I don't intend to try to set the world to rights here, but I would
like to throw my two penn'orth into the debate.
   
If you were a Comms fan just two or three years ago, there was probably a
BBS in your local area, so you could get online at local call rate, although
on the more popular Boards, you often had to wait until the small hours,
because they were always busy.  Nowadays, Boards are much more thinly spread
around, and I'm sorry to say, the general quality has declined (with
noteable exceptions).  So, nowadays it probably costs you more to Dial
you're nearest Board, and it may not be good enough to keep you coming back.
  
I'm not going to discuss the relative merits of The Net versus the BBS,
because there just isn't any point.  It's not a competition anyway, they are
two separate entities, but the BBS Scene is definitely overshadowed by The
Net, because there's a lot of money to be made from it, and it's been hyped
up by the people making the money.  The BBS Scene, on the other hand, has
never shouted about itself, probably because the people at it's heart have
always been Amateurs, who usually end up spending lots of money just to
pursue the hobby they enjoy. 
  
So what's to be done?  How do we halt the decline in the number of Boards?

Well, for a start, let's use The Net to advertise the presence of the BBS
Scene.  I'm sure that there are lots of Net Users out there that don't even
know what a BBS is, never mind what it does.  Some of them may log onto a
Board for the first time, and failing to be impressed by the lack of
flashiness, decide never to bother again.  This is a price that has to be
paid, I think, in order to get to the people who do understand what a BBS is
about, who understand that it's a much more personal relationship than you
can have with a Web-Site.  Also the BBS Column in AMIGA FORMAT really works,
(Thanks Dunkie (SysOp Of @{BG fill}@{"Quest BBS" Link QuestBBS}@{BG background})).  Personally, I got back into Comms
after an absence of a couple of years, after seeing the BBS Adverts in AMIGA
FORMAT.  There must be others out there just like me, so if you're running a
BBS, for God's sake advertise, you're not going to get many calls if no-one
knows you're there.

Next, we need to maintain high standards, because New Users aren't going to
return to Boards which don't have some good Software, or a consistent theme.
I'm quite aware that it can take some time, and much hard work, to get a
Board to a reasonable standard, and this is where we can all help by
spreading the best Software.  I know that todays Cover CDs have loads of
stuff on them, and can make it seem pointless to look for new stuff on a BBS,
but I also think that it's easier to find something on a BBS Filelist, than
trawl through everything on a CD to find something worth adding to your
system.  So if you find something good, then Upload it to your BBS, and let
us all know about it.

New SysOps need to have patience, because todays BBS is less likely to have
Ratios, therefore more 'troughing' goes on, and less Files are Uploaded,
which of course means that it takes longer to build up a good Software
library, and by the time time you have, less of it is likely to be current.
They may also have some teething troubles, which they may not even know
about.  For example, a couple of years ago, a New Board appeared in my area,
but however much I tried, I could not get a connection.  I tried to phone
the SysOp to tell him, but no-one ever answered, so I gave up.  The Board
soon disappeared, presumably through lack of Calls.  Another point I could
make is, be online when your advert says you will.  This might sound stupid,
but I have called Boards, well after their opening time, and had a voice
answering the Modem, and yes, I did double check the time!!!  Nevertheless,
I was still embarassed to have given someone's Wife/Granny/Baby-Sitter an
earful of binary, and the important thing of course, is that it made me very
wary of calling back. 

Let's also look at ways in which a BBS can serve it's Users better.  What
about using them as Virtual User Groups.  I know many Boards are well down
this path, but if it was pushed hard, I think this could go a long way
toward gaining more loyalty from the Users.  After all, people are not going
to run up their Phone Bill just to support a Board, but they are much more
likely to call if there is something else to be gained.  Another advantage
is that most Board's Users are at least fairly local, so there is more
opportunity for face-to-face meetings with other Users.  Most Boards already
have Message areas, what about special areas for Technical Help, and perhaps
Users with specialist knowledge could advertise this on their local Board.
This could then be spread by this very Magazine, so if someone far off
needed help, they could leave a message on the Helper's local Board, and
call back after a few days to pick up their reply, result, more people using
the BBS Network in a rewarding way.

Before finishing, I'd like to say that if anyone has anything to say about
this Article, then let's be hearing from you.  The more Users that join the
debate, the better the ideas that come out of it.

Regards...

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Kevin McAspurn AKA The Rock Giant (Hebden Bridge, West Yorkshire)
