        @{u}The Views & Memories Of A Former SysOp - By Matthew Clayton@{uu}

I would like to start by saying I first got into Computers at an age of
about nine-years-old, and yes, when 8-Bit Computers were at the height of
cutting edge technology.  I first learnt by using, what I can remember, a
BBC Micro Model B.  It was the most advanced Computer at the time, and if
you where lucky, your local School had one.  Well, as I myself suffered
learning disabilities, I was sent to a Private School, where I learnt to
overcome my learning problems and this is where I found I was able to unlock
my skills and show how I could learn, and how Computers could help me right
up to the year 2000, and to this day, I still rely on them heavily.

My first ever Computer was a Spectrum ZX128 +2 (Tape), and WOW!!!  8-Bit
Graphics, and what was so modern, that the Games could be changed and be got
from every Toy Shop, Computer Shop and or Electronic Superstore, i.e. Dixons,
where I got my beloved Spectrum from.  It was not even a year before I had
the hard job of telling Mum & Dad that it was out-of-date, and was just not
flexible for my needs, and I traded it in for a Spectrum ZX128 +3.  And yes,
after not too long I gave it to my Mum, who right upto nowadays has followed
my lead in Computers and has tried to stay with it all.  My next Computer
platform was Amstrad.  Not too long after that I went from the CPC 464 (Tape)
to the CPC 6128 (Disk) and I soon found I was back at my ZX problem, I was
limited by my Graphics and Sound.

1995, the year of Live Aid, and I was just about to discover the world of
AMIGA, and I remember to the very day entering Dixons and looking at the
mega-display that Commodore had paid and layed on for Dixons, and showed my
Mum that that would be my future for many years, and after being told to
wander round the Shop, I found that Mum had juggled the books (like parents
do) and had got me my first AMIGA 500, the Batman/New Zealand Story Pack,
with a mega 512K Memory (I didn't know at the time what that was).  Let me
see, oh yes I soon found the power of 16-Bit Graphics in a some what 4096
Colours and being a young cheeky ten-year-old, I saw my first digital stored
picture and what a suprise, SHE WAS NAKED!!!  I soon saw the power of AMIGA
and worked my way through the AMIGA range, from 500 to 1200 and then to a
1200 + Blizzard 1260-060, and I soon found it was time to 'Tower-Up', so
armed with a hacksaw and my AMIGA, I towered my baby up and installed some
demo BBS Software, and I found myself for some time running a BBS, and I am
so glad that I shared my memories with AMIGA in the BBS World, and I always
have and will remember the memories I have with AMIGA.

After a long, and can I say a sad time of thinking, I have made the hard
choice of deciding to sell ALL my AMIGAs, and move to my newly built PC.  I
know what you might be thinking, and saying that this whole article is to
give a bad name to AMIGA and make people sell-up, well...No, after a long
time of AMIGA and seeing all my friends get PCs, I still decided to hang in
with the AMIGA, but due to my College Work I have had to decide not to spoil
or disturb those brilliant memories I have of AMIGA, and informed my friend
Dunkie (SysOp Of @{BG fill}@{"Quest BBS" Link QuestBBS}@{BG background}/Editor Of @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}), that I would be saying
Goodbye to the AMIGA.

But I will always speak well of AMIGA, and have enjoyed the memories I have,
and how it has helped me get on in life.  So I would like to end with my
last thought, maybe one day I can return back to AMIGA when they get back
on their feet, and if they do, I will not hesitate to return back to AMIGA.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Matthew Clayton (Ex-SysOp Of Tribal Mirage BBS/TABBS 2000)
                (AMIGA User 1995-1999 (14 Loving Years Of AMIGA))
