             @{u}What I Miss From The BBS Scene - By Hugo Wilkinson@{uu}

The Readers Articles seem to be loosely based around the same thing over
Last Month's @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, so I thought I would start to supply a steady
stream of (hopefully) interesting articles.

The first is going to be about what I believe the BBS Scene currently lacks.

As Jim Delaney (SysOp Of @{BG fill}@{"Electric Box BBS" Link ElectricBoxBBS}@{BG background}) pointed out, the technology
behind BBSes is exactly the same as that used by the Internet.  In other
words, whatever the Internet supplies, the BBSes can do also (even a
miniature version of IRC isn't going to be difficult)!!!

These facts alone has somewhat surprised me in the huge decrease of BBS
Users.  Using a BBS is so much more of a learning and different experience
that again, it amazes me that so many people left!!!

The next thing I'm concerned about is that, now that everyone has had a
taste of the Internet.  Why aren't they returning to the BBSes???

What the bugger makes the Internet sooooo good that BBSes should be chucked
out of the window altogether???

I think the answer lays in information.

<Employ old man type speech>

Back in 1994 when I first started to use BBSes (and got my AMAZING £80
2400bps Modem (damn FAST for the time I'm telling you!!!)), I called all
the BBSes I could find under the Sun.  Even the AMIGA FORMAT 300+ page
AMIGA STARTER Compilation Magazine (a 6 month special), had about 6 A4 pages
dedicated to BBSes.  You could even sign up to Compuserve over a BBS at the
time (not sure if you still can though)!!!

Anyway, even if the Internet had existed and had so many Users and
facilities as it does today, BBSes would still be a hugely popular thing.

During this period of time, it was not uncommon for people to call European
BBSes (especially one called AMIGA Central, I think) and at that time the
UK's most busiest AMIGA BBS was AMIGAOne.  It was so busy infact, that the
SysOp had 3 lines and 2 PREMIUM lines.  You could either pay for a 
subscription and Download Files, or not pay a subscription and use the
Premium lines for Downloading.  You could also speak (in real time) to up to
20 other people on the BBS as the biggest BBSes kept a 24-Hour Network open.

That was a point in time where there were hundreds of Callers a day, rather
than a month.

In 1996 we saw a slow transformation of BBSes.  Hundreds of teenager's took
up the band wagon (with the help of MAX's) and started to open small BBSes
with not nearly the amount of facilities and Mail Networks, but a huge File-
Base within (usually) specialist subjects, i.e. There was like a BBS for
THIS and a BBS for THAT (e.g. Adults, Astronomy, Hacking etc), and because
of these specialist areas the SysOps were able to put alot of effort into
producing a top quality BBS with all the latest info and programs on a
particular subject.

This new age of virtually FREE BBSes caused huge traffic reductions to the
larger subscription BBSes.  AMIGAOne was a perfect example to fall at this
time.

By late 1997 there were only a few big BBSes left (and I can only really
remember Test Drive BBS as being hugely successful).  Then another
transformation took place.

Due to the lack of big GENERAL BBSes, all the specialist BBS's took heed
and started producing File-Base's for the masses.  Utility sections galore,
Game sections galore, and probably the biggest turn over of Calls made by
Pornography.

This was all free and because of the general selection of SysOps around at
the time (under-paid students hehe), the Files were all coming from the same
place.  Once a File hit one BBS, it was on ALL within a week.  It became
like a PC Market.  Lots of different names for the same bloody thing!!!

Then, the Internet attack proceeded, and what anyone could get on any BBSes
was suddenly available with nice graphics and point'n'click features.

If BBSes had stayed in a sort of 'specialist' mode, then I don't think the
BBS Scene would be in such a mess as it is today.

Infact, if you're a SysOp reading this, ask yourself "What can my BBS
significantly offer over any other BBS I know of?"...

I would imagine that for most of you the answer would be a 'Mail Network'.
@{BG fill}@{"FluffyNet" Link FluffyNet}@{BG background} used to be the biggest (apart from FidoNet of course), but now
even that has died...(good too, that put me out of business!!!) <GRIN>

On a lighter note, I would love to see the BBS Scene take off again.

It is an excellent community of people, and the whole feel of BBSes is a lot
nicer than that of the Internet, including a damn lot cheaper in some cases
too!!!

Over and out...
                                              
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Hugo Wilkinson (SysOp Of Innovations BBS)    
