       @{u}Reply To 'The BBS Scene' - By Neil Williams (SysOp Of TKG BBS)@{uu}

I've just read a letter in Last Month's @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text} from Chris Seward (my
boss, I'd better be nice ;)), the Editor of AMIGA Information Online (AIO)
no less, and was astounded by what I read.  He talks of the days of the BBS
in 1995 are now gone in 1999.  In the UK this is true, at least partially
for the moment, but is certainly not true in places where cheap 24-Hour
Internet Connections are readily available.  The USA is undergoing a huge
BBS revival, after quite some downfall (far more so than in all of Europe).

The difference is ADSL.  Chris talks about not many SysOps having taken the
plunge with TelNet BBSes.  This is because it is almost impossible in the UK.
It's fine to talk about All-Day Sunday BBSes, using the various Free Weekend
Services, but this is not practical!!!  Not many Call Part-Time BBSes via
Modem, how many would Call a One-Day BBS running at a speed often less than
1KB/S?

There are many success stories being related in the Networks about *NEW*
TelNet BBSes.  It's even got to the point where some USA SysOps are taking a
holier-than-thou stance with respect to Dial-Up BBSes - as they are now
taking hundreds of Calls a week, and don't understand that in the UK the
government has been restricting ADSL in the name of `increasing competition'
(of all the excuses)!!!  It won't be until 2001 that we have a reasonable
coverage of ADSL capable exchanges here.

It is also important to see the Internet for what it is.  It uses similar
technology to existing Phone Lines, the difference being that it is all
permanently connected (or will be once *USERS* world-wide get 24-Hour
Internet Connections) and `long distance' charges no longer exist - funnily
enough, Arthur C Clarke predicted this in one of the 2001 novels, though if
it was 3001 it wasn't much of a prediction :-)

I realise that near the end of his Article, Chris makes a distinction
between Dial-Up and TelNet BBSes, but please remember that they are one and
the same, they are not mutually exclusive, they do the same thing: only the
method of connection is different.  A TelNet BBS is still a 'BBS' in every
meaning of the word, just like a Dial-Up BBS.  It is important for us not to
say "The BBS is dead, long live TelNet" - then you give potential Users the
impression that TelNet BBSes are about to go the way of Gopher.  Try "The
BBS is dead, long live the BBS" instead!!!

Let's not forget the BBS' other strength - as home of the FTN Networks.
What is a Web-Site, if nothing more than a very non-interactive and
impersonal BBS?  What is UseNet, but Pornography, Spam, and Death Threats?
FidoNet still exists, there are still 15,000 and more Nodes in it, and
Russia is leading the way in FidoNet expansion with new BBSes (yes, even
Dial-Up Systems) opening all the time.  What about AMIGANet?  Last count,
more than 500 Nodes in EuroAsia alone.  The Internet is being used today to
move Fido-style Networks around, using E-Mail 'tunneling' and TelNet to
connect Mailers in *EXACTLY* the same way as it would be done over a Dial-Up
Line.

Oh, and a final word:  Yes Chris, I know Anthony Brice - I bought his copy
of the Zeus BBS Software when he closed the Backyard BBS :-)  In fact, I
liked Zeus BBS so much I bought the company!!!

<plug> http://www.bleach.demon.co.uk/zeus/ </plug> ;-)

And for the record I'm not writing this to sell more copies of Zeus BBS, I
genuinely believe in the BBS Scene, and BBS Software is my way of
contributing.

