        @{u}AMIGA: Back For The Future? - By Dunkie (SysOp Of Quest BBS)@{uu}

AMIGA Changes Hands...AGAIN!!!  Do we jump up for joy at the News, or simply
shake our heads in despair, knowing that yet again the AMIGA's troubled life
story starts ALL over again?

GATEWAY, after all this time indeed dumped the AMIGA, and came clean over
it's true reasons for buying the AMIGA in the first place, just as I hoped
they would do, but the new owners of the AMIGA name, AMINO, in my opinion
are just as obscure as some of the previous owners of the AMIGA.  A newly
formed company, that appears to have no manufacturing experience, that has
just forked out a reported $5 million to purchase the AMIGA in name alone.
Even though this company is owned by former AMIGA Inc employees, even though
they of ALL people must truly care about the AMIGA, doesn't guarantee any
future for the AMIGA at all, as the AMIGA Community has dwindled drastically,
and still IS doing, ever since GATEWAY scrapped plans to build the next-
generation AMIGA MCC last year :(((

Ben Vost (Editor Of AMIGA FORMAT) stated that in the last 6 months, his
readership has dropped by approximately 40%, showing that a majority of the
AMIGA Community appears to have had enough, and called it a day.  Can you
blame them?  The last 6 years have brough nothing but heartache to the AMIGA
Community, with AMIGA constantly changing hands, new AMIGAs being promised
and then undelivered, and even though the AMIGA looks to be in the best
hands of any of it's previous owners, for many in the AMIGA Community, all
of this has come too late :(((

As I said a few Issues back, the AMIGA doesn't have a future in it's present
form.  The PC Industry is so huge now, with it's ever expanding new
technology readily available to the Buyer on the High Street.  The AMIGA has
no real friends in the High Street, and a lot of work will have to be done
to gain High Street confidence in the AMIGA platform again, and the last 6
years of AMIGA history will not help in this task.

In my opinion, it won't matter what happens with the AMIGA platform in the
next few months, it won't matter what kick-ass machine they develop and
eventually build, because without adequate marketing or availability to the
Buyer in the High Street, their efforts will be, to be honest, worthless.

Basically, before the AMIGA can truly be resurrected, the new owners of
AMIGA have one hell of a mountain to climb, and it's terrain is going to be
the toughest they've ever seen...good luck guys...you're going to need it!!!
