        @{u}How To Run A Successful BBS - By Dunkie (SysOp Of Quest BBS)@{uu}

Here at @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, we get many complaints from SysOps that Callers have
dwindled to such a level, that basically they no longer put any effort into
their BBSes, but just leave them online in the hope that things will improve.
Speaking as a SysOp rather than the Editor of @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, I can tell you
that this is not the case everywhere, and if you are prepared to put some
time and thought into your BBS, it does pay off.

@{BG fill}@{"Quest BBS" Link QuestBBS}@{BG background} is my own BBS, and I've been running studies for the last 3 Years,
basically to monitor BBS Activity.  Now if I was to tell you that last year
alone I had an average of just over 180 Calls a month, how would that
compare to you?  Furthermore I can tell you that none of those 180+ Calls
had anything to do with Polling Mail, because that facility isn't available
on my BBS yet!!!

If you take into consideration that @{BG fill}@{"Quest BBS" Link QuestBBS}@{BG background} is also only a part-time BBS,
not 24-Hours, how do you explain it's popularity?  The answer is plain and
simply, because I put the effort into making @{BG fill}@{"Quest BBS" Link QuestBBS}@{BG background} a place that people
will want to visit time and time again, and this is something that ALL
SysOps should be looking at achieving!!!

I've created this Article to assist SysOps in achieving results, it's my
little way of trying to help SysOps to basically help themselves, and
indeed the restore the reputation of the UK BBS Scene:-

                          @{b}T O P   T E N   T I P S@{ub}

@{b}[01]@{ub} Try to make your BBS different by customising your BBS Software,
     giving your BBS a fresh new-look, with the use of Colourful ANSI Menus
     and Screens.  This will seperate your BBS from other BBSes using the
     same BBS Software, and give your BBS a unique feel to the BBS User.

@{b}[02]@{ub} Adapt your BBS to your Users' needs, listen to their needs and act upon
     where you can.  Remember, there's no point in offering a service no-one
     wants.  If you don't provide what your Users want, they'll find another
     BBS that will!!!

@{b}[03]@{ub} Always answer your Users' Mail, the amount of SysOps who ignore Users'
     Mail is disgusting!!!  Always converse with your Users, it'll make them
     feel that YOU, the SysOp, is approachable and create that more friendly
     environment, which in my opinion is the BBS' biggest weapon in the
     fight against the Internet...take heed!!!

@{b}[04]@{ub} Keep your BBS Users informed on any new developments on your BBS, any
     new additions and services, and any forthcoming news regarding your
     BBS.  Remember that Users are Gold to your BBS, without them your BBS
     is worthless.  You must provide Users with an incentive to call again,
     again and again, and providing Users with information on the progress
     of your BBS, is one such way of doing this.

@{b}[05]@{ub} Try to keep your BBS open through the Night, most SysOps agree that the
     majority of Callers call during late-evening/early-morning.  This means
     your BBS will be available for the biggest percentage of BBS Users.

@{b}[06]@{ub} Make sure you stick to your specified BBS operating times, there's
     nothing more frustrating for Users, than listening to someone shouting
     "Hello" down the Modem, or the Modem not answering when your BBS is
     advertised to be online.  This will most likely, no, I'd say definetly,
     result in Users not attempting to call your BBS again!!!

@{b}[07]@{ub} Make sure you have a wide selection of File areas on your BBS, making
     sure that it's wasy for your Users to find what they are looking for.
     Don't cram loads of Files into one File area, try to split them down
     into seperate File areas, making it easier for your Users to list each
     area and see what you have to offer.  Managing your File areas in this
     manner, also creates the illusion that you have more than you really
     have, again a good selling point for your BBS.

@{b}[08]@{ub} Try and add Files to your BBS on a regular basis, try adding a few
     Files daily, even if it's only a few.  You'll find that when your Users
     come online, that those few Files will have grown to a decent amount
     when they next call, assuming your Users do not call everyday.  This
     looks good to the User, and is more likely to result in Users calling
     more regularly.

@{b}[09]@{ub} Be generous with or even abolish File ratios on your BBS, there simply
     isn't any point in enforcing this policy on today's BBS.  Users tend
     to use their limit, and then usually grab anything they can lay their
     hands on to Upload, which usually results with you having unwanted
     Uploads, in my case I used to get handfulls of crappy WAV Files, which
     were neither use or ornament to anyone, including myself.  So, why not
     take the view that the User is calling your BBS at HIS expense, in
     preference to anyone or anything else, and be grateful that he/she is
     calling your BBS, rather than someone elses!!!  If you respect this
     judgement, you'll find your Modem buzzing :)))
    
@{b}[10]@{ub} Advertise your BBS everywhere you possibly can, and make it clear the
     between times your BBS is operating.  AMIGA FORMAT now runs a *FREE*
     BBS Adverts column, so if you want to advertise your BBS in the pages
     of AMIGA FORMAT, then send your BBS Advert (no more than 30 words) to
     amformat@futurenet.co.uk, putting Reader Adverts/BBS Adverts in the
     Subject Line.  If you ask other SysOps to advertise your BBS for you
     on their BBSes, always, I repeat, always return the favour!!!

This Article is merely my opinion, and should be treat accordingly, but it's
an Article that when put into practice, as the evidence indisputedly shows,
does infact achieve benefitial results for your BBS.  If you'd like to add
your input to this Article, or indeed if you agree/disagree with this
Article, then get in touch with @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, and let us hear your voice.

As Kevin McAspurn's @{BG fill}@{"Article" Link KevinMcAspurn}@{BG background}, in this very Issue of @{FG highlight}CoNnEcTiOnS@{FG text}, states,
"The more people that join the debate, the better the ideas that come out of
it", and I whole heartedly agree with that statement.  So...don't just sit
there silent, let us ALL listen to YOUR unique perspective on this matter,
and together we may be able to solve some of the problems that are plagueing
the UK BBS Scene today!!!
