   @{u}Zeus BBS Software - By Neil Williams (SysOp Of The Killing Ground BBS)@{uu}

Allow me to introduce Zeus Developments.  Our main product is the Zeus BBS
package, and that's what I want to talk about (which is a good idea, since
this is a BBS Magazine after all).  If this turns out as more of an Advert
than an Article, SORRY!  But read it anyway, hey?

Zeus started life in 1992, born out of a need for something different in the
BBS World.  Nothing out there looked or felt like an AMIGA program - it was
all MS-DOS monsters or AMIGA OS 1.3 throw-backs.

So, two AMIGA SysOps got together and started work on Zeus, which went
through extreme programs of coding and testing over four years, until it's
final commercial release in 1996 at the World Of Amiga Show in London.  At
this time Zeus won many awards, and gained top scores in reviews in
prestigious Magazines such as AMIGA REPORT and CU AMIGA.

Sadly, after four and a half years of producing Zeus updates at a minimum
rate of seven a week, the original Authors stopped work and became all but
uncontactable.  After (literally) years of attempts, Zeus was finally bought
out by a group of three dedicated SysOps in April 1999.  The already
world-beating package has just got better.

Firstly, of course, we ensured Year 2000 compliance.  There were minor
issues with this, mainly in places where two digit dates are input, but now
Zeus is almost guaranteed to be fully operational through the Year 2000.

Next, we went for the bugs and feature requests which have piled up since
1996.  Yes, there were a few.  The bugs, in general were easy to squash
when you consider how big Zeus is.  Zeus is a very modular system, so
finding any errors is fairly easy even if there is 50MB of source to go
through.  Adding new features will always take time, especially if you also
take time to properly beta test each new thing added (well, there's some
time cut ;).  Internet support for TelNet BBSing is very important now and
we are working towards this steadily.  You can of course use the freely
available TNServ or Shareware TelSer with Zeus with excellent results.

While nothing hugely major has taken place between Zeus 1.1 and 1.3, we are
planning on an all-out powerful Zeus 2 for some date in the future.  This is
being kept under wraps at the moment.  I suppose I should reassure potential
buyers that Zeus 2 will be a very cheap upgrade for Zeus 1 owners (perhaps
even free to all long time Users, but this isn't definite and is not legally
binding, so ha!).

Perhaps instead of talking on and on like this, I should let you know some
of the features packed into Zeus.  I'm using and commenting on our ZeusInfo5
pack, which should be available on BBSes, AMINET and our Web-Page quite
soon.  For more detailed information, please see this pack!

Zeus is compatible with any AMIGA running OS 2.04 or higher which has more
than 2MB of memory.  Zeus requires ARexx, which is supplied with all AMIGA
OS versions since 2.04.  Zeus will take advantage of newer AMIGA OS features
without sacrificing compatibility.

Zeus tries to combine flexibility with ease of use.  It is configured using
a plethora of GadTools GUI programs.  The I/O between the user and the BBS
is controlled using a "ScriptSet" and menu screens, utilising Zeus' command
set of several hundred functions and the special ControlCodes for any
displayed text.

Our main claim is that Zeus can perfectly emulate any other Bulletin Board
in existence, a bit like its namesake.  So, lets have a look at the feature
list and talk about what each feature means.

@{u}BBS Features@{uu}

- Fully ARexx driven:
   - All menus are rexx scripts and are therefore totally configurable
   - Optional global command system
   - Could even be used to run a system exactly like CompuServe!

This basically is what the whole thing is about.  Zeus can take any form
you choose.

- No Hardcoded text:
   - Every single character in Zeus is configurable!
   - Auto ANSI code removal and 8 bit translation

Not only does Zeus allow you to change all the text shown to Users, it also
has features for providing compatibility with whatever terminal or
preferences those Users have.  As above, Zeus can automatically convert ANSI
to plain ASCII (no need for you to define two menu sets to do this) and also
will convert 8 bit ANSI graphic to ASCII - i.e. it will automatically
convert the IBM style character graphics to something viewable without an
IBM font!

- Powerful 'Watcher' system:

Zeus' concept of a 'Watcher' is separate from each line node.  In other BBS
programs, you might have the ANSI Watcher built into the node program, and
you might have to run the node program for each line you have.  Not so with
Zeus.  The Watcher for each line is separate, allowing you to either not
have a Watcher loaded (saving memory when you don't need to communicate with
the User) or even have more than one Watcher loaded.

   - 20 Function Key slots for running external programs or inserting text
   - Data screen shows useful BBS information:
      - Number of Users
      - Number of Calls today (and total Calls)
      - Number of Files/Messages online
      - Graph showing all-time and session Calls statistics
   - ANSI Watcher:
      - Ultra fast 2-16 colour ANSI display
      - Supports AMIGA codes
      - Optional pre-scroll 'jumpy' mode for faster scrolling.

The standard Watcher used by Zeus is the powerful and extremely fast ANSI
Watcher.  It supports all ANSI control codes, even down to ANSI music!

   - RIP Watcher:
      - HiRes 16 colour vectorised graphics display
      - Local RIP terminal

RIP is the standard for BBS graphics, showing Users vector and bitmapped
Graphical User Interfaces along with the normal ANSI displays.

   - CON Watcher
      - Open a shell-like Watcher window on any public screen

A simple CON Watcher, like that used by some other BBS programs.  Although
having some of the limits of a CON display (poor ANSI capability) it is
capable of being opened as a window on Workbench or Zeus' Control screen
(discussed later).

- IEMSI Support:
   - Allows Users to login instantly

A powerful addition supported by some terminal packages on the AMIGA and
many on the PC.  When the User calls the BBS, their terminal package will
communicate with Zeus and automatically log them on, and even set their
preferences.

- ANSI Music Support:

As mentioned above, Zeus even has native support for ANSI music!  Yes, such
a thing exists - maybe it's not pretty but it's fine for little jingles
after uploading or something similar.

- Optional Control screen:
   - Configurable menus for starting BBS related programs (GUI Editor)
   - Screen settings:
      - Any resolution
      - 2-256 editable colours
      - Any font
      - Supports IFF backdrops
   - Zeus programs can put 'icons' on the Control screen
      - Example 'ChatStatus' program graphically shows whether the SysOp is
        available for paging or not.  Just click to change!
   - The Control screen is public so you can set other programs to open
     their windows on it - e.g. TrapDoor.
   - Control can also be reduced from a screen to a window on Workbench,
     saving memory and still giving full BBS control and information
   - Control can be iconified onto Workbench at any time

The Control screen is how you as a SysOp communicate with Zeus.  It is like
a Dock and Workbench mixed together - you can put icons and menus on the
screen/window and use these to launch Zeus programs, edit the BBS, launch
automated tasks, etc, and also it is somewhere where Zeus programs iconify
themselves to.

@{u}Text System@{uu}

- Supports 256 menu sets and 256 languages
- Possible 66050 filename combinations for EACH text file
- GUI Menu Set and Language editors
- Optional text buffering system
   - Definable number of files to keep in memory
   - Optional file length limit

The text is the pre-made screens shown to your Users.  Zeus (as mentioned
above) can filter them based on your User's preferences.  Texts can also
contain control codes - Zeus' special character combinations which are
replaced by special texts.  We'll discuss these later.  Zeus also has a text
buffering system!  If you run a busy BBS, with many languages and menu sets,
it will be far better if Zeus could show menus and texts which are required
often from memory, rather than getting them from disk each time.  This is
what the buffering system does.

@{u}BBS Nodes@{uu}

- Unlimited amount of nodes

Really, Zeus can support any number of nodes you wish to set up!  And, with
Zeus' library concept, each node can take less than 10KB each - a far cry
from those BBS packages which require you to run another copy for each node!

- GUI Node setup program
- Serial options:
   - Supports any serial device/unit
   - Baud rates from 110-292000
   - Carrier, DSR and Rad-Boogie (the high speed mode) can be
     enabled/disabled
   - Full control over parity, char length, handshaking, stop bits
   - Can also be configured to accept TelNet connections
   - Floating baud rates supported

Zeus is fully compatible with all serial devices.  Whatever you wish to
connect Zeus to, it'll work.

- Nodes can be started from any 'front end' software or from the supplied
  Connector, ZMailer, TelNet or other provided 'front end' utilities.

Zeus includes a full and complete FidoNet mailer!  This highly featured
program is also very low maintenance - once set up, it'll work for as long
as it's needed.  The mailer uses a standard TrapList compiled NodeList, so
exisiting installations can be used in Zeus.

- Each line can have restrictions placed on it seperately, allowing you to
  define the times Users can get on with parameters including:
   - Minimum and maximum access of Users to let on
   - Minimum and maximum baud rates to allow use of the BBS
   - Disable logons (only allow FidoNet or SysOps Callers)
   - Go mail only (don't let users get past the FidoNet mailer)
   - No Answer!  With this, you can run a part-time BBS with ease, as you
     define when Zeus is allowed to answer the 'phone - no more having to
     put the BBS on/offline manually!

This is a very nice, very powerful feature of Zeus.  It is beyond what many
other BBS packages are capable of.

@{u}User Specifications@{uu}

- Unlimited number of Users
- Each User has their own directory

As each User has their own directory, it can be used to keep Files waiting
for them, to place QWK and BlueWave packets, for them to use themselves to
backup important data even!

- Fast User list scanning:
   - Alphabetical or Chronological
   - Forwards or Backwards
- GUI User Editor

As with most Zeus components, the SysOp has a full graphical interface to
manage Users with.

- Banned User support with full AMIGA DOS wildcards

Using this, not only specific Users can be banned, but by using wildcards
you can ban offensive names that you don't want on the BBS before the User
even gets past the login prompt!

- UserManager program:
   - Delete Users (with AMIGA DOS wildcard support)
   - Strip Users (who haven't called in 'x' amount of days)
   - UnDelete Users
   - Rebuild and Optimise User file

Like so much of Zeus, the User database can be managed automatically. Just
stick what you want in a Cron utility (one is provided) and it'll be run
every day, every month, every 12 minutes, whatever you want.

- BootUser utility chucks Users offline

Where would we be without this? :-)

@{u}Bulletins@{uu}

- 'RealTime' GUI Bulletin Editor
- Minimum/Maximum access
- Bulletins can be set to expire at a certain date/time

A strong feature in Zeus, Bulletins can not only be used for SysOp notices
(since Zeus can tell a User at logon if any have been updated) but also
for statistics or other automatically generated texts.  The expiry feature
also contributes to Zeus' low maintenance requirements.

- CLI Bulletin Manger:
   - Add/Remove bulletins
   - Update bulletins which have been changed recently
   - Set expiry infomation

Of course, the tool for use from the CLI or automatically keeping the
bulletins up to date.

@{u}Message Specifications@{uu}

Every message area in Zeus is assigned to an 'mb' library.  An 'mb'
(message base) library defines the low-level functions that manipulate
the messages as they are stored on disk.  Each area can be assigned a
different 'mb' library, or every area to the same one.

This means that various formats of messages can be accessed by Zeus
completely transparently, allowing foreign programs to maintain or use the
message base (or specific areas within) as well as Zeus, even a PC, Mac or
Linux box working over a network can now access the same message areas as
Zeus!

Currently available message libraries are:

   - mbzeus.library     - an extremely fast indexed message system.
   - mbstarmsg.library  - standard FTSC-1 message system (as used
                          with TrapToss and Foozle).
   - mbuunews.library   - RNEWS format UseNet news.

- Zeus Internal FTS Mail Processor

Zeus comes with a full and complete FidoNet mail processor.  It is fully
featured, and is something which if not shipped with Zeus would certainly
be an expensive package to buy in it's own right!

The program is known as "ZMP" - the Zeus Mail Processor.

   - 5-dimensional operation

Sees addresses as "2:442/107.0@fidonet", but you can also use "2:442/107.0"
if you want.

   - Superlative Import speeds

ZMP is fast.  Take the whole FidoNet backbone of several megabytes a day
with ease, export it to a hundred downlinks just as quick.

   - Auto-area creation

Create an area straight into the BBS, or have it skip the BBS and just
passed through to downlinks.  Or even disable auto-creation of areas.

   - Built-in AreaFix support
     - Uplink support
     - Full control

If you've ever used a BBS package with no AreaFix support, this will be a
god send.  It's a fully featured AreaFix robot - your Users need never
bother you about fixing in or out of areas, they can talk to the AreaFix
robot and do it themselves.

   - Pass-through areas.

Don't want an area on your BBS, but do want to pass it on to points or
other downlinks?  Set it as passthough.  Easy.

   - Echomail file attach support.

Zeus even supports the odd practise of attaching files in echomail areas!

   - Fully-featuring routing system

Wildcard capable routing ensures your Netmails go where they're supposed
to.  Run a small BBS with one routing line, or a World HUB with a hundred -
doesn't matter, Zeus can handle it.

   - Automatic Archive/Packet type switching on detection.

What if a downlink can't support the advanced archiver or packet type you're
sending them?  Well, the message they send to complain will automatically
switch Zeus into a compatible format for them!  If they send ZIP, so does
Zeus.  If they switch one day from LHA to LZX, Zeus switches with them, no
questions asked.  Of course, this can be turned off for each linked node
individually if needed.

   - FTS-1 (2D), 39 (4D), 48 (4D) and 45 (5D) packet import/export support.

All ratified FidoNet standard types of message packet are supported, even
the two separate 4D standards, ensuring compatibility with every other
system out there.

   - Inbuilt Tick Processor and Hatcher

A Tick system is also built into ZMP, which ties into the Zeus File
sub-system and is capable of auto-creating new tick echoes, tying them into
a BBS file area.

   - Name->Address Remapper

Do people keep spelling your name wrong?  Set up a few different spelling
in the Remapper and Zeus will catch them and send them to you properly.

Or, have you or another User moved address?  From the BBS to a point
perhaps?  Set them up here and Netmails will always find their target.

   - Area flow statistics
      - Keep data on number and size of messages passing per week
      - Supplied program to configurably output this data, e.g. for posting
        in areas/networks

Zeus keeps tabs on the messages passing through each networked area.  Want
to see how many messages have passed through HOLYSMOKE this week?  Check it
out easily:

